ves who got information
unlawfully, the question is: How did they get information [about Harry] whi=
ch wasn=E2=80=99t in the public domain? And the inability to demonstrate wh=
ere the information comes from creates an inference of hacking.

=C2=A0

But there=E2=80=99s an unusual feature with this particular claim because N=
ews Group says Prince Harry knew about the possibility of his claim for mor=
e than six years, and therefore it falls outside the statute
of limitations. So the first question is whether this is time-barred, and h=
ere there is an additional layer of complexity because it=E2=80=99s asserte=
d that [Murdoch=E2=80=99s company] did a deal with Buckingham Palace to giv=
e Prince William good publicity. And as a consequence of that, members of t=
he royal family=E2=80=94William and Harry=E2=80=94[agreed they] wouldn=E2=
=80=99t sue. So there becomes the question of first, did Harry know about t=
he claim, and second, did he know about the compromise of the claim?

=C2=A0

That=E2=80=99s quite a lot! Obviously, this trial isn=E2=80=99t just about =
how reporters got salacious information, is it?=C2=A0

=C2=A0

It=E2=80=99s a slightly more interesting claim in some respects, because th=
