underline;color:#d40000;">detailed</a> on Monday, Lively=E2=80=99s highly s=
pecific complaint=E2=80=94and the stories it generated=E2=80=94were built o=
n information retrieved from the cellphone of <strong>Jen Abel</strong>, a =
Baldoni publicist who worked for <strong>Stephanie Jones</strong> at Jonesw=
orks. Abel handed over her phone
before leaving the firm this summer, and Jones, in turn, provided the sensi=
tive contents to Lively=E2=80=99s legal team under subpoena. But did Jones,=
 in effect, <em>invite</em> that subpoena as a way to sidestep her confiden=
tiality obligations to a former client? Matt noted her conspicuous absence =
from Lively=E2=80=99s complaint (and the <em>Times </em>story, too). I=E2=
=80=99ll add this: As far as I can tell, Jonesworks was the <em>only</em> e=
ntity subpoenaed. Baldoni himself didn=E2=80=99t get one. That seems=E2=80=
=A6 odd.<br/><br/>So
given this, <em>why</em> did the story of Lively=E2=80=99s complaint get ou=
t? Was it, to echo what Lively told the <em>NYT</em>, to pull back the curt=
ain on sinister retaliatory tactics aimed at those who speak up about misco=
nduct? Perhaps. That seems to be the prevailing narrative. And, certainly, =
Lively should be able to address alleged sexual harassment on a movie set w=
ithout being targeted by a coordinated smear campaign. Filing with the Civi=
l Rights Department may indeed be a prelude to a lawsuit:
It commands the gravitas of a government body and offers certain privileges=
, like reduced defamation risks and the perception of seriousness, without =
requiring immediate escalation.<br/><br/>But here=E2=80=99s a more cynical =
theory: Cognizant that Baldoni was on his way out as a client, Jones decide=
d to dish dirt as an act of<em> her own </em>retaliation. Abel=E2=80=99s ph=
one, I=E2=80=99ve been told, wasn=E2=80=99t owned and issued by Jonesworks.=
 So Jones took her <em>employee=E2=80=99s</em> phone=E2=80=94was that even =
legal?=E2=80=94and used its
contents to arm Lively=E2=80=99s team with damaging material. If so, the la=
test stories may be the <em>result</em> of yet another layer of P.R. rat-fu=
cking.<br/><br/>Is that what happened? I can=E2=80=99t say for sure, but <s=
trong>Bryan Freedman</strong>=E2=80=94Baldoni=E2=80=99s lawyer=E2=80=94cert=
ainly thinks so. Freedman told me that upon learning her firm was being fir=
ed by Baldoni=E2=80=99s company on August 30, Jones insisted she <em>couldn=
=E2=80=99t</em> be terminated until the expiration of her contract=E2=80=94=
and instead, demanded $200,000. When
