<table class=3D"c4" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspaci=
ng=3D"0" role=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspa=
ce:0pt;word-break:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"r" style=3D"padding-=
bottom:32px;"><div style=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;In=
ter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;=
line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"m=
argin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong><em>Eriq Gardner</em></strong><strong>:=
 What, precisely, is
Harry=E2=80=99s legal claim here, and what does he need to establish to pre=
vail?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p sty=
le=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Mark Stephens</em>: The claim is ess=
entially that there was an unlawful acquisition of information by the newsp=
aper=E2=80=94sometimes by hacking, but sometimes by deception. Given that i=
n previous cases, judges have made findings about particular journalists be=
ing involved with particular private detectives who got information
unlawfully, the question is: How did they get information [about Harry] whi=
ch wasn=E2=80=99t in the public domain? And the inability to demonstrate wh=
ere the information comes from creates an inference of hacking.</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bott=
om:0px;">But there=E2=80=99s an unusual feature with this particular claim =
because News Group says Prince Harry knew about the possibility of his clai=
m for more than six years, and therefore it falls outside the statute
of limitations. So the first question is whether this is time-barred, and h=
ere there is an additional layer of complexity because it=E2=80=99s asserte=
d that [Murdoch=E2=80=99s company] did a deal with Buckingham Palace to giv=
e <strong>Prince William</strong> good publicity. And as a consequence of t=
hat, members of the royal family=E2=80=94William and Harry=E2=80=94[agreed =
they] wouldn=E2=80=99t sue. So there becomes the question of first, did Har=
ry know about the claim, and second, did he know about the compromise of th=
e claim?</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>That=E2=80=99s quite a lot! Obviously,=
 this trial isn=E2=80=99t </strong><strong><em>just</em></strong><strong> a=
bout how reporters got salacious information, is it?=C2=A0</strong></p><p s=
tyle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-=
bottom:0px;">It=E2=80=99s a slightly more interesting claim in some respect=
s, because the trial is going to delve into some of the backroom deals that=
 Harry says were done,
and are probably more embarrassing, both for the newspaper and the palace. =
Was there a secret deal for the newspaper to give good publicity to the roy=
al family, and in return, they undertook not to sue? The judge has to make =
that determination first. If the newspaper loses the time-bar issue, I thin=
k it=E2=80=99s almost certain that Harry will win at least some of the unla=
wful acquisition of information claims. The time-bar issue is really import=
ant, which is why the newspaper is bringing in a very
eminent king=E2=80=99s counsel to cross-examine Harry.</p><p style=3D"margi=
n:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=
<strong>Harry is scheduled to be in the witness box for four days. Any idea=
 what he=E2=80=99ll be questioned about?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;m=
argin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">They=
=E2=80=99re going to try and destroy him in cross-examination, because Harr=
y=E2=80=99s case is pretty straightforward. Harry says, =E2=80=9CThere may =
have been people in the
palace who knew about this unlawful intrusion, but <em>I didn=E2=80=99t kno=
w, </em>and therefore I wasn=E2=80=99t able to exercise my rights.=E2=80=9D=
 The newspaper, on the other hand, says, =E2=80=9CWell, of course you knew,=
 and you had every opportunity to bring your claim, and you just missed the=
 time.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Do you have any idea what damag=
es Harry needs to win to no longer be in the red for bringing this legal
proceeding?</strong>
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0=
;">I think the answer is that this is not an economic case. Harry has made =
it clear that he=E2=80=99s not in it to either cover or make his cost. He w=
ants accountability. He feels that his life has been intruded upon, that it=
=E2=80=99s had an impact on his relationships with others. And then you lay=
er on top of that, the way in which the media treated Princess Diana, his m=
other. And of course, you start to understand why this is such an
issue of principle for Harry.=C2=A0</p></div>
</td></tr></tbody></table>
